3. Necessary Architectural Improvements for Enterprise Deployment
To scale from a structural MVP to a robust, maintainable, production-ready system, the following improvements are strongly recommended:

1. Migrate to a Frontend UI Framework (React/Next.js or Vue)
Current Issue: Mixing raw HTML string concatenation with complex JS logic (
admin.js
 strings are massive) makes the app extremely prone to XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) vulnerabilities, is difficult to maintain, and complicates state management algorithms. Fix: Adopting React or Vue will componentize the UI, manage the lifecycles gracefully, heavily mitigate XSS, and allow for much faster developer iteration.

2. Move from CDN Scripts to NPM Packages
Current Issue: The Firebase SDKs and Chart.js are loaded globally via <script> tags in 
index.html
. Fix: Install dependencies via NPM (npm install firebase) and let Vite bundle them natively. This enables features like tree-shaking (removing unused Firebase code) which vastly reduces the load time of the initial JavaScript bundle on mobile connections.

3. Implement Static Storage for External Images
Current Issue: Hotlinking high-resolution external images from Wikipedia or Unsplash causes the browser to block them locally or on restricted domains (yielding ERR_BLOCKED_BY_ORB or CORS errors). Fix: Create a process that downloads the external images, resizes/compresses them uniformly to WEBP formats, and uploads them to the internal Firebase Storage bucket. The app should only serve images from its own domain.

4. Centralize the Backend (Deprecate Apps Script)
Current Issue: Having Cloud Functions handling Orders while Apps Script handles Enquiries creates a split, fragmented backend footprint characterized by different deployment pipelines, log structures, and auth layers. Fix: Port the Google Apps Script 
doPost
 functionality into a new Firebase Cloud Function (submitEnquiry). The cloud function can still talk to Google Sheets via the googleapis library if the Sheet is mandatory, but centralizing the logic improves security.

5. Transition to TypeScript
Current Issue: A global JavaScript state where an orderItem floats around without shape guarantees leads to runtime crashes (e.g. attempting to do math on a string ID). Fix: Introducing TypeScript interfaces for 
Product
, CartItem, and 
Order
 ensures that developers catch typing errors immediately in the IDE, drastically decreasing production bugs.

6. Improve Firestore Data Rules
Current Issue: Security rules are fairly broad. While submitOrder is locked down, read operations have minimal throttling. A malicious actor could repeatedly poll the products listener. Fix: Enforce stricter API restrictions in the GCP Console, tighten Firestore wildcard rules, and implement App Check to ensure only your authorized frontend domain can communicate with the backend.